h3. Issue Summary
For some reason, custom fields that contain some sort of their description between parenthesis in their title are created between brackets, and brackets are not well-read by calendar events when searching for a JQL that contain these fields.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Create a custom field on JIRA that has some sort of description in its title, for example:
** *Select List (cascading)*;
** *Select List (Multiple choices)*;
** *User Picker (single user)*
# Create an issue filling this custom field;
# Still in JIRA, create a JQL that will contain this custom field, like:
** {{project is not null "Custom Field[Select List (multiple choices)]" is not null}}
# Go to Confluence and access any calendar;
# Create an event with event type *JIRA Issue Dates*;
# Select the server where you created the custom field;
# Select the JQL option and insert your JQL there.

h3. Expected Results
You will be able to follow the next steps to create your JIRA event.

h3. Actual Results
The JQL is successfully verified, but we receive a "*Something went wrong*" error that doesn't allow us to create the event.

h3. Workaround
Save your JQL as a filter and either use the JQL option to insert {{filter = <FILTER_ID>}}, or choose the filter option to pick it.

Right now it is not possible to fetch

page via API and access custom emoji image.

 

Lets say I want to render page and I call:
{code:java}
GET https://{instance-name}.atlassian.net/wiki/rest/api/content/{content-id}?expand=body.view,body.storage,body.editor2,body.editor,body.atlas_doc_format,body.dynamic,body.export_view,body.styled_view{code}
 

 

Custom Emoji comes with such a data, 
example from some storage formats:

 
{code:java}
<p><ac:emoticon ac:name="blue-star" ac:emoji-shortname=":Custom-Emoji:" ac:emoji-id="db293667-6684-4383-b378-7964a40f0429" ac:emoji-fallback=":Custom-Emoji:" /> </p><p />{code}
 
{code:java}
{
  "type": "emoji",
  "attrs": {
    "id": "db293667-6684-4383-b378-7964a40f0429",
    "text": ":Custom-Emoji:",
    "shortName": ":Custom-Emoji:"
  }
},{code}
 

 

There is no way to download image behind this emoji id.

 

 

Please consider to allow to fetch emoji, example:
{noformat}
GET https://api.media.atlassian.com/file/{emoji-id}/image?width=32&height=32{noformat}
or include direct url to emoji in response.

h3. Issue Summary

With the [Confluence Cloud REST API to search content|https://developer.atlassian.com/cloud/confluence/rest/api-group-search/#api-wiki-rest-api-search-get], users can use the [CQL|https://developer.atlassian.com/cloud/confluence/advanced-searching-using-cql/] to retrieve content based on different parts such as the "creator" of them.

If the creator value is specified to an invalid author (I.E. "fake_user"), it will return results of content created by Anonymous users.

h3. Steps to Reproduce

# Either using an [API token|https://support.atlassian.com/atlassian-account/docs/manage-api-tokens-for-your-atlassian-account/] to retrieve the results or directly using the browser, make sure to add an API search with CQL like the following:
{code}
https://INSTANCE.atlassian.net/wiki/rest/api/content/search?cql=creator='INVALID_ACCOUNT'
{code}
# By looking into the IDs retrieved, to retrieve the creator, use the [API to get content|https://developer.atlassian.com/cloud/confluence/rest/api-group-content/#api-wiki-rest-api-content-get]
{code}https://INSTANCE.atlassian.net/wiki/rest/api/content/<ID>{code}
# Search for the *CreatedBy* value:
{code}
"createdBy":{"type":"anonymous",}
{code}

h3. Expected Results

No results should be retrieved as the creator is using an invalid name. Instead, an error should be displayed or no results at all.

h3. Actual Results

Results for content created by an anonymous will be displayed.

h3. Workaround

Currently there is no known workaround for this behavior. A workaround will be added here when available

Currently, When someone creates a page from a template with variables, they’ll fill out a form with text fields or lists for each variable in the template before the page opens in editor mode for editing other fields like placeholder text, date, etc. We see the below message for this "TemplateVariableInputDrawerQuery" request:
{code}This template uses variables. Once you fill them in, the information you supply will become part of the content on your new page.{code}

Suggestions: This is bad UX user experience and very confusing to the end-users and not very intuitive. I would recommend that this process is conducted in one stage i.e. all updates performed in edit mode (not having a different page/UI for adding a variable).
